There are indications that President Muhammadu Buhari may be part of the dignitaries that will be at the Moshood Abiola Stadium in Abuja to drum support for the Super Eagles against Ghana’s Black Stars in Qatar 2022 World Cup Play-Off. According to the Minister of Youth and Sports Development, Sunday Dare, the president may possibly turn up for the decisive match. “I was in Lagos on Tuesday, March 22, and the President asked me why was I not in Ghana and I realized that the President also knows that there is a Ghana match,” Dare was quoted by Ghanasoccernet.com.   Ronaldo admits tough test  against North Macedonia     Salah leads Egypt ‘ World Cup war’ against  Senegal     WTT Doha: Aruna edge Chinese star in crunchy tie   He added that it is not certain that the President would attend the second leg in Abuja but he said, “He has not given me 100 percent assurance but he is likely going to show up here (second leg) on the 29th as a surprise,” Dare said. Meanwhile, the Video Assistant Referee (VAR) has been installed at the stadium for today’s match. The VAR has been tested and certified for the all-important clash that will decide the team that will join four other African teams in Qatar. A FIFA official confirmed that the VAR technology has been tested and certified for the match.